{"editorCode":" ;Thalis Theorem\n\n;The procedure \"riddle\" constructs horizontal and oblique line segments. \n;The horizontal ones divide the oblique ones into two parts as following:\n;a) The bottom part of the red oblique segment has length 80 avatar-steps, and the top part has length :x avatar-steps.\n;b) The bottom part of the black oblique segment has length :x avatar-steps and the top one has 180 avatar-steps. \n\n;Can you find a value of the variable :x which causes the alignment between the black and the red segments?  \n\n;Click the papyrus button in order to read the instructions and some questions that will help you during your engagement with this activity.\n\n\nto riddle :x\nsetpencolor [255 0 0]\nlt 90 fd 200\nrt 120\nfd 80 ;the bottom part of the red oblique segment \nrt 60 fd 150 bk 150 lt 60\nfd :x ;the top part of the red oblique segment \nsetpencolor [0 0 0]\nrt 95.3\nfd 180 ;the top part of the black oblique segment \nlt 35.3 bk 150 fd 150 rt 35.3\nfd :x ;the bottom part of the black oblique segment \nlt 35.3\nbk 200 lt 90\nend\n\nclean\nriddle 150\n","hiddenCode":[],"sceneCode":"","cameraPos":{"x":0,"y":1.2246467991473532e-14,"z":200},"character":"Bird","notes":" TASK\n---------------------------\nRun the command \"riddle 150\" and enable the variation tool (by clicking on the trace of the avatar). You can find the requested value of the variable :x by changing its value using the slider. \n\n\n1) Can you interpret the solution geometrically?\n2) Write a new procedure in order to construct the same shape, but with the red and black horizontal parts ALWAYS aligned. \nTIP: It does't have to include a variable.\n\n\n\n ","sliders":{},"objects":[]}